R Examples for Shrinkage

Principal Component Regression Examples

The first principal component (PC1), explains 86.7% of the total data variation, while the first three components explain more than 95% of the total variation.

Since each principal component is a linear combination of the original data, we can inspect the elements of the rotation matrix to understand the PC meaning. This can be challenging in some cases. In particular the first column \(u_1\) is:

round(pcfat$rot[,1],2)
##    neck   chest   abdom     hip   thigh    knee   ankle  biceps forearm   wrist 
##    0.12    0.50    0.66    0.42    0.28    0.12    0.06    0.15    0.07    0.04

This PC weights indicate that the first PC is a combination of all body measures with more weights on central body measurements abdom, chest and hip, and less weight on extremity measurements.

Scaled principal components (recommended)

Since the central body measurements are larger and the PC decomposition depends on the variables scale, we should re-scale all variables before applying the PC method.

pcfatr<-prcomp(cfat,scale=TRUE)
summary(pcfatr)
## Importance of components:
##                           PC1     PC2     PC3     PC4     PC5     PC6     PC7
## Standard deviation     2.6498 0.85301 0.81909 0.70114 0.54708 0.52831 0.45196
## Proportion of Variance 0.7021 0.07276 0.06709 0.04916 0.02993 0.02791 0.02043
## Cumulative Proportion  0.7021 0.77490 0.84199 0.89115 0.92108 0.94899 0.96942
##                            PC8     PC9   PC10
## Standard deviation     0.40539 0.27827 0.2530
## Proportion of Variance 0.01643 0.00774 0.0064
## Cumulative Proportion  0.98586 0.99360 1.0000

First principal component weights

round(pcfatr$rot[,1],2)
##    neck   chest   abdom     hip   thigh    knee   ankle  biceps forearm   wrist 
##    0.33    0.34    0.33    0.35    0.33    0.33    0.25    0.32    0.27    0.30

Now all weights are very similar, and the first principal component represents an approximate average of all original variables explaining 70.2% of the total variation.

The remaining principal components will be orthogonal to the first one. The second principal component has negative values for the central body measurements and positive values for the extremity measurements, which indicates a contrast between these two groups of measurements. This will result in high score values (the x in pcfatr ) for observations with high extremity measures and low central body measurements; and low score values for observations with low extremity measurements and high central body measurements.

Second principal component weights

round(pcfatr$rot[,2],2)
##    neck   chest   abdom     hip   thigh    knee   ankle  biceps forearm   wrist 
##    0.00   -0.27   -0.40   -0.25   -0.19    0.02    0.62    0.02    0.36    0.38

Orthogonality of PC weight vectors

t(pcfatr$rot[,2])%*%pcfatr$rot[,1] # This product is zero except for numerical rounding error
##               [,1]
## [1,] -9.714451e-17

Checking for X outliers

PCA can be very sensitive to outliers, but detecting outliers in multiple dimensions is harder. If the m-dimensional data has a multivariate normal distribution, we can use the fact that the mahalanobis distance \(d^2=(x-\mu)^\top\Sigma ^{-1} (x-mu) \sim \chi^2_m\). We can compare the theoretical quantiles of the \(\chi^2\) with the observed mahalanobis distance to the center mean \(\mu\) for each observation \(x_i\). This can be calculated as the chi-square cdf inverse evaluated in \(i/(n+1)\) where \(i\) is the order of the distance \(d_i\). We can use the function cov.rob from the MASS package to estimate the covariance matrix.

library(MASS)
sigfat<-cov.rob(cfat)
mdist<-mahalanobis(cfat,center=sigfat$center, cov=sigfat$cov)
n<-dim(cfat)[1]
p<-dim(cfat)[2]
quant.mdist<-qchisq(1:n/(n+1),p)
plot(quant.mdist,sort(mdist)); abline(0,1)

We could repeat the PCA after removing these points. You might like to try this.

Regression on the principal components

Now we will use these PCA results in the regression. First we fit a model to brozek using the 10 original predictors, and fit a second model using the first two PCs. Note that the first model fit might be unstable since many predictors are correlated.

Since abdom has the largest weight in the first principal component, and ankle and abdom have the highest weights in the second component, we can select a combination of these two variables.

moda<-lm(fat$brozek~.,data=cfat)

Example 2: meatspec data set

We have data from 215 pure meat samples and 100 predictors coming from a Tecator Infratec Food and Feed Analyzer. The fat content was measured along with 100-channel spectrum of absorbances.

We split the data into:

  • Training sample: First 172 observations

  • Testing sample: Remaining 43 observations.

We can measure model performance using the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE): \(\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i- \hat{y}_i )^2/n}\)

data(meatspec,package="faraway")
trainmeat<-meatspec[1:172,]
testmeat<-meatspec[173:215,]
mod1<-lm(fat~.,trainmeat)
summary(mod1)$r.sq
## [1] 0.9970196
# function to calculate the rmse
rmse<-function(x,y) sqrt(mean((x-y)^2))
rmse(fitted(mod1), trainmeat$fat)
## [1] 0.6903167
rmse(predict(mod1,testmeat),testmeat$fat)
## [1] 3.814

Now use PCs to predict the response and compare the RMSE. We will use library pls and function pcr instead.

library(pls)
## 
## Attaching package: 'pls'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     loadings
modpcr<-pcr(fat ~ ., data=trainmeat,ncomp=50)
#summary(modpcr)
#RMSE with 4 PCAs
rmse(predict(modpcr,ncom=4),trainmeat$fat) 
## [1] 4.064745
rmse(predict(modpcr,testmeat,ncomp=4),testmeat$fat)
## [1] 4.533982
#compare coefficients from LS estimate and PCR estimate
plot(mod1$coef[-1],xlab="Freq", ylab="Coef", type = "l")

coefplot(modpcr,ncomp=4,xlab="Freq")

#Why 4 PCAS? Use screeplot to figure this out.
meatpca<-prcomp(trainmeat[,-101])
plot(meatpca$sdev[1:20],ylab="PCAs Std Dev",xlab="PCA number",type="l")

Four PCs is a reasonable selection according to the scree plot. But we want to select enough number of PCs to minimize the RMSE.

set.seed(123)
# Minimize RMSE using function RMSEP
pcrmse<-RMSEP(modpcr,newdata=testmeat)
plot(pcrmse)

which.min(pcrmse$val)
## [1] 28
pcrmse$val[28]
## [1] 1.854858
#Use 10-fold Cros-Validation
set.seed(123)
modpcrcv<-pcr(fat~.,data=trainmeat,validation="CV",ncomp=50)
pcrCV<-RMSEP(modpcrcv,estimate="CV")
plot(pcrCV)

which.min(pcrCV$val)
## [1] 20
meatpred<-predict(modpcrcv,testmeat,ncomp=18)
rmse(meatpred,testmeat$fat)
## [1] 2.127134

With 18 PCs we get a RMSE on the test sample close to the smallest RMSE achieved of 1.854858 with 28 components.

How would the results change if we scaled X in the meat example?

modpcrscaled<-pcr(fat ~ ., data=trainmeat, scale=TRUE, ncomp=50)
#summary(modpcr)
#RMSE with 4 PCAs
rmse(predict(modpcrscaled,ncom=4),trainmeat$fat) 
## [1] 4.210361
rmse(predict(modpcrscaled,testmeat,ncomp=4),testmeat$fat)
## [1] 4.748898
#Screeplot
meatpcascaled<-prcomp(trainmeat[,-101], scale=TRUE)
plot(meatpcascaled$sdev[1:20],ylab="PCAs Std Dev",xlab="PCA number",type="l")

In this example we see that unscaled is slightly better than scaled. This makes some sense because all of the spectral measurements are on a common scale of measurement. Scaling is more important when the different X variables are all in different units, so we need to remove the scaling effects.

Lasso examples

Example 3: state data

We have data from 50 states:

  • Population: population estimate as of July 1, 1975

  • Income:per capita income (1974)

  • Illiteracy:illiteracy (1970, percent of population)

  • Life Exp:life expectancy in years (1969–71)

  • Murder:murder and non-negligent manslaughter rate per 100,000 population (1976)

  • HS Grad:percent high-school graduates (1970)

  • Frost:mean number of days with minimum temperature below freezing (1931–1960) in capital or large city

  • Area:land area in square miles

We want to predict Life Expectancy.

Use the function lars from library lars to fit a lasso

library(lars)
## Loaded lars 1.2
data(state)
statedata<-data.frame(state.x77,row.names = state.abb)
head(statedata)
##    Population Income Illiteracy Life.Exp Murder HS.Grad Frost   Area
## AL       3615   3624        2.1    69.05   15.1    41.3    20  50708
## AK        365   6315        1.5    69.31   11.3    66.7   152 566432
## AZ       2212   4530        1.8    70.55    7.8    58.1    15 113417
## AR       2110   3378        1.9    70.66   10.1    39.9    65  51945
## CA      21198   5114        1.1    71.71   10.3    62.6    20 156361
## CO       2541   4884        0.7    72.06    6.8    63.9   166 103766
plot(statedata)

modls<-lm(Life.Exp~.,data=statedata)
summary(modls)

#No model equation in function lars
modlasso<-lars(as.matrix(statedata[,-4]),statedata$Life.Exp)
plot(modlasso) #standardized coefficients vs t (restriction upper limit)

The x axis is the value of the L1 norm of the coefficients relative to the norm of the LS solution t. As this value increases more predictors enter into the model. For small values of t only murder stays active. For larger values of t, variables HS.Grad Population and Frost enter into the model. The optimal value of t can be selected by Cross-validation:

set.seed(123)
cvmodlasso<-cv.lars(as.matrix(statedata[,-4]),statedata$Life.Exp)

sv<-cvmodlasso$index[which.min(cvmodlasso$cv)]
sv
## [1] 0.6464646
#Lasso coefficients
predict(modlasso,s=sv,type="coef",mode="fraction")$coef
##    Population        Income    Illiteracy        Murder       HS.Grad 
##  2.259631e-05  0.000000e+00  0.000000e+00 -2.379447e-01  3.492634e-02 
##         Frost          Area 
## -1.558616e-03  0.000000e+00
#use help(predict.lars for more details)
#LS coefficients
coef(lm(Life.Exp~Population+Murder+HS.Grad+Frost,data=statedata))
##   (Intercept)    Population        Murder       HS.Grad         Frost 
##  7.102713e+01  5.013998e-05 -3.001488e-01  4.658225e-02 -5.943290e-03

The lasso coefficients are shrunk with respect to the LS coefficients.

Example 4: Lasso for meat data

trainy<-trainmeat$fat
trainx<-as.matrix(trainmeat[,-101])
meatlasso<-lars(trainx,trainy)
# Select t by CV
set.seed(123)
cvml<-cv.lars(trainx,trainy)

which.min(cvml$cv)
## [1] 2
svm<-cvml$index[which.min(cvml$cv)]
svm
## [1] 0.01010101
# Compute predicted values for test data with selected t
testx<-as.matrix(testmeat[,-101])
predlasso<-predict(meatlasso,testx,s=svm,mode="fraction")
rmse(testmeat$fat,predlasso$fit)
## [1] 2.132223
#predicted lasso coefficients
predlasso<-predict(meatlasso,s=svm,type="coef",mode="fraction")
plot(predlasso$coef,type="h",ylab="Coefficient")

From the coefficients plot we can see that only few frequencies are used to predict the response, which is eqivalent to a variable selection method result.
